The course is easily compared with corporate retail computer based trainings that I have done throughout the years.  What that means is that it suffers from a variety of flaws that are a mix of educators/managers having limited subject knowledge, unclear instructions, and a very low expectation of the abilities of the student.  It presents the idea that, if a case or contact is obviously unhappy, the contact tracer must have done something wrong.  If a case is not immediately receptive to the contact tracer, the contact tracer is too inept to handle the situation and should immediately hand it over to the supervisor.  I counted 3 completely wrong answers in quizzes and the final test.  Some vignettes did not match the course material in the videos they were part of.  Finally, the technology section needs to be scrapped.  The instructor has no subject knowledge and went off on a political tangent on how China and Korea were doing everything right by tracking their citizen's every move.  The instructor even went as far as suggesting a non-existent, near impossible to regulate app that would have a similar effect in the US.
Sample phone calls were too long.  People do not want to stay on the phone that long especially when sick.   Presenter talked to slow.  There should be a shorter course for Registered Nurses.

While this course provides basic details on the disease (COVID19) and the basis of contact tracing, my personal idea is that the contact tracing is not done strongly and properly enough. The methods proposed by Johns Hopkins Uni (and I believe that they are applied nation-wide in the US) is ineffective in stopping the spread of the virus. No lock down, and trace down to the last minute detail. Even "talking for 5 minutes" is not considered as "at risk" factor, all close contacts are just "advised to stay home" (where there will be no supervision, no support, no test and no check-up). I'd say this is a fun course to take, but not a practical one.

Besides being a bit arbitrary and misandric, the most important oversight is the course could be subtitled, "You, too, Can be a Contact Tracer!" because it presents the practice as though anyone could reach out to cases and contacts without any means to prove that they're authorized to do so. It also presumes the ubiquitous availability to everyone of social media, smartphones, and other technological devices that in fact are not universally present. It never mentions this social/economic divide even though the majority of COVID 19 patients are in the economic bracket where lack of availability of such technology is most prevalent.

Enjoyed the course, however, nothing was included about documentation which is crucial.  It would have been helpful for the role-play to include the caller documenting the necessary information obtained during the phone call...no one just sits there and talks.  At least there should have been a screen shot showing what the caller documented for the "initial" call, and follow-up "check-in" calls, as well as for urgent progressive/worsening symptoms.   This is an important piece because some of us are being asked to complete this course in order to begin contact tracing duties asap.  Is the documentation done via a portal of the health department?  Or the laboratory?  Or is it just an excel document that each individual contact tracer completes each day.  Is there a program/application (software) and can it provide notifications for when a case or contact needs a follow-up phone call ("check-in") since this process can snowball easily with new cases/contacts being added each day?       Lastly, I heard the caller mention that she could provide resources, however, we never saw an example of how that plays out.  Does she pull out a clip board with listings of local resources and proceed to give information to the person?  Or does she tell the person someone else (i.e. a resource person) will call her?   More clarity in these areas would help in order to ensure we have what is needed for the best possible outcome.  I appreciate all that you are doing to preserve the health of our communities and I thank you for this educational opportunity.

All of my saved notes & constructive comments seem to have just disappeared.  The quizzing (presumably intended as a teaching tool) was inconsistent, as if the author just forgot about them after the first few introductory lessons.The video lectures were excruciatingly slow, with no speed control, so I wound up downloading the transcripts for note-taking purposes.   For most of the Sample Calls, the speakers were adequately identified, but then all identification was abandoned, and the transcript was just one long run-on paragraph of dialogue text; meaningful only as a review of undifferentiated but perhaps useful phrases.Style: FWIW, I found it distracting that more than ten percent of the sentences started with the usually superfluous word "So".  There also seemed to be an inordinate number of redundant phrases & sentences.  Enough to confuse the structure & perhaps emphasis of their paragraphs.  Given that there is such demand for this sort of information that it seems to have been at least opened by over a third of a million browsers,  It might be worth a good editorial style review or even rewrite using Occam's razor. Every time I went to the help/trouble shoot  page, it tells you to log in, but when you click the log in button nothing hapoens.  Because I spent so much time problem solving, it took me several hours longer  to complete the course than it should have. Because of this frustration, I am very reluctant to take additional Coursera trainings, and would only recommend to a friend with major reservations and warnings to "prepare to be frustrated."  There is no "contact us" link, no customer service phone number. After a lengthy search,  I found a phone number, but it turned out to be a fax machine.  But most important,   during the enrollment process, I opted in to get a certificate.  After completing the course, additional frustrating time spent trying to find out how to obtain the certificate has turned up nothing.  The congratulatory e-mails I reveived say nothing about how to get the certificate.  Another long search through your web site turned up nothing. Logically, clicking on "certificates" seemed appropriate, but no. I would like to be proven wrong, that you actually do have customer service. I invite one of your staff to contact me at Ejholt6122@aol.com or by phone 215-514-5353 and let me know how to obtain this certificate for the course that I worked so hard to pass. Thank you, have a great day, and be well. Sincerely, E. Holt, MS-CCC-SLP

I wanted to provide some feedback regarding contact tracing training offered through Coursera/Hopkins  I completed the training - and I know there was mention of the need to get an interpreter for families speaking a language other than English - but there was no mention of Deaf/HH persons.  I know, especially in Maryland, DC and Va - we have a large number of deaf and hard of hearing persons - so I would like to ask that this be added to your training - so your tracers are not caught off guard and don't know what to do - thank you

I found the mechanics of the course confusing.  Why do you care if my time zone is different than yours? When I tried to correct it, there were no time zones (EDT,CST, etc.) but if I was in Ulan Bator you had my back. It became a Jeopardy question: "A city in the US Eastern Time Zone". To continue, sometimes you clicked the blue box, sometimes you needed to use "next".  The choices weren't always obvious. When it came time to complete the final test, I had to refresh the browser to get to it (thanks,for noting that, but I shouldn't have to do it). When I saved my certificate the first time, it didn't have a file extension so my computer couldn't open it. I still don't know how that happened, but a download later was OK. Structural problems aside, I thought the content was well explained, and the questions brought out the material. I would have left out the section on smart phone tracing by blue tooth contacts, since it is not in place yet, and seems impractical. (1) need everyone to have a smartphone, (2) they have to agree to be tracked (not likely w/o major privacy controls on data retention and access) (3) GPS accuracy is about 3 meters without augmentation - that would exponentially increase the false contact rate.

I think it would be great to talk about how many of the mechanisms used in contact tracing can further perpetuate inequities in the communities that have been most impacted by the pandemic.  Many historically marginalized populations don't trust contact tracers, and relying on technology, phones, etc. leaves many people who don't have access to technology more susceptible to contracting and spreading the disease. Lastly, I think it's important to talk about false positive tests as well even if they don't pose the risk that false-negative tests do.

There is a final exam problem that is not properly stated. If it had been started correctly I would have gotten it right. The Question was Something like: what is the difference between private and confidential information.I believe that the correct answer (according to the testers) didn't include a "difference".  I believe that the testers are using the following as the correct answer:"Confidential information includes information about a person's medical history, including a positive COPVID-19 test."Well that is also private information so there is no "difference." In order have a "difference" you have to state something about private information also which wouldn't be included in confidential information.If there had been stated a "difference" I would have answered correctly, but I chose an alternate answer as a guess: "contract tracers will learn confidential information, but not private information during a call." It is not entirely true, because confidential information is private, but there is some seriously private information that will not be shared with a contract tracer.So there is some problems with what definition one wants to use. The definitions of "private" verses "confidential" are not in our handout of definitions.

This is a great course, though very densely packed with a lot of information. It's kept in bite-sized chunks, but it absolutely took longer than the 5-6 hours listed in the description. My only other complaint is that for the most part, it assumes that the general population will be ready and willing to comply with instructions to isolate/quarantine; the course certainly does have a few examples where a sick person doesn't agree right away, but very quickly, their Example Person is convinced. The last year of living in the US has shown that a significant number of people will not be swayed so easily, and my years in customer service tell me that there will absolutely be people who yell, scream, deny the virus, flat refuse to quarantine/isolate, or hang up and block the number. None of these scenarios are even mentioned in the training. A large part of the training also focuses on teaching you to paraphrase (essentially repeat back) to the case or contact nearly everything they say to you. My years in Call Center Supervision tell me that this is a bad idea. A minute or two of having everything repeated back, and nearly everyone starts to get annoyed and just wants the call to be over. I absolutely agree that empathy is important, as is confirming if you have a question or didn't understand. However, constantly telling someone, "So what I heard you say was" and "It sounds like you're feeling" and "I hear you saying that" will, in my experience, only serve to annoy and break down any rapport you might otherwise have, as the person will feel like you're being robotic and using stock phrases instead of actually connecting with them.

Overall, this course provided excellent coverage of not only COVID-19 but also the job of a Contact Tracer. The videos were helpful to give deeper insights into various issues.  There were a few questions that I found confusing.  Some had to do with grammar issues.  (For example, one question on a quiz asked if the Contact Tracer's question was leading, closed, open, etc.  I don't recall the specific question, but it is similar to the following:  Suppose the Contact Tracer said:  "On Sunday, you stated you had a fever; is that correct?"  According to one of the lessons, that would be a "checking" question;  however, I consider it also a closed question because such a question is generating a yes or no response.  (Yet, the test answer does not acknowledge that.)  Another situation where I think one of the test answers was misleading had to do with grammar.  What was used should technically have referred back to the last pronoun, but the answer referred further back in the sentence. I sensed what the question was getting at but decided to go the proper grammar route which resulted in an incorrect answer. The final test had two answers I still don't agree with.  One had to do with the use of technology checking fevers at night.  I have read there are some to track fevers and not only at night.  Similarly, I have read that recent studies show Covid-19 germs can be spread via it getting on shoes from the floor. (I realize it is possible I misunderstood the question/answers.)  The other questions I got wrong are clearly my own errors.  This course has been very helpful and has further motivated my interest in becoming a Contact Tracer.  It would be a great way to utilize my cumulative skills and at the same time help lessen the spread of Covid-19.  Thanks to John Hopkins University, Coursera, Dr. Gurley and others who created and offered this course.  Sincerely, Patricia Cyr, Peoria, AZ

This is not a linguistics course and understanding how to communicate is important but an exam on terminology definitely is not.  And, while Ms. Gurley is undoubtedly gifted and passionate in her chosen field, the vocal fry is about the worst I've ever heard.  Only one person I know personally can rival it.  I would highly encourage Ms. Gurley to research the term and consider changing her speech and intonation.  To me, it really matters.  It was terribly distracting throughout the series. Thank you for offering this very informative course at no charge. For the most part, it was clear. However, there were 3 questions on the final assessment that gave me pause.  If it states... Select All That Apply... I thought that indicated that there was more than one correct answer. The question that asked about what is appropriate to say to develop rapport... I was reluctant to choose... "I know what you mean." I chose it because it said... Select All That Apply. We can't really KNOW what they mean for certain... but it was better than the other options ie. I know how you FEEL.  (I hear you.... is always best, I agree.)  Also... the question about stepping in droplets from an infected person.  I had the same issue with this one.  Nevertheless... I am also wondering whether this MIGHT be a means of transmission IF the person handled the shoes shortly after stepping in the droplets and then failed to wash his hands. An example might be... trying on shoes at a store filled with unmasked shoppers and employees... some coughing/sneezing and a couple of people in the infectious stage. But it wasn't addressed in the coursework, so I was hesitant to choose that option... but it said... Select All That Apply.  In addition... another question that I scored correctly, according to the coursework, caused me to stop to consider recent news reports. A couple of days ago, I read articles that said that the CDC has changed its guidelines concerning how soon a case can end isolation. It now states that after only 24 hours without a fever (without medication and with improving symptoms) as opposed to 72 hours as stipulated in the coursework. The minimum of 10 days still applies, as I recall.  Thanks again for offering this course. I learned a lot of useful information.

Re: content and presentation, I give this course a solid FIVE STARS.  The  course material is very informative and thorough at least at a basic, introductory level. The instructor is quite adept in her presentation of both the key points and the supporting information. All in all, an excellent course.HOWEVER, website navigation is extremely problematic, irritating and, at times, downright scary. Watching the videos was always fine. But then, at the end of the video, I would click to advance to the quiz, I'd take/complete the quiz and get my grade...and then it always got very confusing as to how I was supposed to get back to start the next  section. I figured out how to do it after the first couple sections, but it's very sloppy and inefficient and always left me wondering if it gave me the proper credit for completing a given section.  It always did, but I also always had to go to "Grades" to make sure. Shouldn't have to do that...But the coup de grace, was that, after I completed the "High-Risk Situations" section it skipped me to the Final Exam, right over the "Ethics" and "Communications" sections. I found this out after I started to take the Final, and the questions turned surprisingly to those two topics. After completing the Final, I also discovered that the system DID give me grades (100% for both!) as if I had viewed the material and taken the quizzes.  Once I saw that I was being asked about material that I hadn't covered in the coursework, I thought about bailing out of the Final. But I knew that would be a sure way to use up one of the two FAILs. So I winged it and managed to pass the Final with a fairly respectable grade. I'm sure I would have done much better, even aced it, had I been able to cover ALL the material I was being asked about. And, had I not decided to look at my Certificate shortly after I passed it, I may have been able to try to take the Final again for a better/perfect grade. But as soon as I clicked on the Certificate page, I was out of the course, with no chance to get back in and redeem myself.So...in terms of content,  A+. In terms of website "logistics" and user friendliness, D-.  Truth to tell, I feel very cheated by the system.

Also see the APIs released by both Apple (IOS) and Google (Android) that permit exactly this sort of warning through Bluetooth on smartphones. Teenager is defined as a post-Tween generally over12 and under !8 years old in most locales. Misleading term - A 17 teenager is just as competence as a proxy for translation as an 18 year old (officially Adult). Simply substitute CHILD for TEENAGER in this question and it will be fair ------------------------This needs to be taken up with the author of the curse and updated. Please advise.

I came into the course with public health preparation.  At some moments I found it tedious to the point that I was getting irritated with the vocal fry of the presenter (which was very mean and I had to check myself).  On the other hand, I thought it covered a lot of material efficiently.  I wondered about the effects of presenting wrong behavior. I think this is tricky since people tend to remember things they see.  Also, I personally bristle when someone calls on the phone and calls me by my first name.  (Perhaps this is generational...) Situations are different, but generally it was my practice in public health nursing to formally address my patients.  Perhaps using first names gets around discussions of gender preference, but one can always ask how a person wishes to be addressed.   I was sorry that the items I answered correctly didn't supply a link to the correct answer.  I went back to find the answers and this required going through the entire sections again to find the answers.  At the end of the course, there is really not a direct link that leads you to the certificate., nor direction for what steps one might take to become a contact tracer.

Dear Colleagues:Thank you for this interesting course.In general, the course was well designed, with sensible sequencing of content. I did wonder why you didn't mention the complete process of contact tracing as an "advance organizer" and include the important point that there are differences in local protocols of contract tracing (though these were adequately discussed in the later parts of the course). I make this point not as a criticism but based on my experience teaching research and health informatics to students ranging from undergraduate levels to students in Masters and PhD programs. The use of 'advance organizers" turns out to be very effective in STEM education.The videos all had good camera work and audio. The cases-contacts and contact tracers were convincing in their portrayals. When we filmed complex patient care for virtual hospital systems we built, we had an expert panel present during the filming but another expert panel who viewed the edited videos. While your video clips and supporting educational discussions were adequate, I was surprised at times by what seemed unplanned lapses in therapeutic communication between case-contact and contract tracer. And, I am not being critical here; I have filmed thousands of minutes and edited these down to 800 video minutes of clinical simulations--certainly, a few interactions slipped past panels that I wish I could have redone. What we did in our virtual worlds was to create study guides that went with the sims and when we found sections of videos in which we would have liked to do a better job, we made them into  learning moments within the study guides. I am guessing you had a limited budget and tight time frame, so I want say that I found your course both engaging and substantive. I wondered a bit about the assessments. They are not quite what some would call "authentic assessments" of knowledge gained. However, the type of assessment you used is still common in many undergraduate programs and post-secondary school technical programs. I would have liked to seen short video clips in the knowledge assessments that were not ones shown during the learning modules, and embedded in such clips were both good and not so good practices for collecting information by phone. There is an interesting body of educational research related to students (at all levels) being able to recognizes and differentiate good and less-good practices and harmful practices in healthcare delivery, including therapeutic communication related to collecting subjective and objective information from a case-contact.As a context for my comments, I have led research teams that designed and built evidence-based adaptive learning engines and that also had the capacity to collect data on end-learners development of misconceptions. I feel your course had no need for that level of learner interaction with content, but I mused how interesting it would be (especially in these times) to be able to assess misconception development in both learners who would become contact tracers as well as actual cases and contacts. Again, I appreciated your course and took your course so I might work in my retirement as a part-time contact tracer.Keep up the good work.With thanks and best regards,Jay Shiro Tashiro, PhD, BSN, BA, RN

I thought the course was informative. I'm still uncertain about the usefulness of contact tracing when there are large numbers of infected people. I also wonder about the 14-day quarantine for a contact. Convincing someone to stay in quarantine for 14 days while they show no symptoms would likely be a challenge which wasn't addressed in the course. The course example eventually developed symptoms. No facts or statistics were given to justify 14 days versus 7 days. There is also no information to justify the set points used for designating someone as a contact in need of quarantine. How big a swath would an infected individual cut based on normal activities in an urban environment? Huge numbers of people could be unnecessarily quarantined.

There were a couple of cases where I only realized after the fact that there was special significance to certain terms and phrases. I would like for those to have been made clear right up front. The most obvious example was the special significance of the terms "Cases" to identify the PERSONS who were positive for COVID-19, and "Contacts," which has a broader significance in general usage in the English language but in this specific case has ONLY to do with people who were in contact with an infected person during the period when they were infected. It mystified me why the distinction was made that those two terms were "too technical" and therefore off-putting to use in contact tracing conversations. It took a while for me to grasp that it was their particular usage *in this context* that made them too esoteric or technical to use. Clarify this up front, and say that that's what you're doing, and I would have gotten it immediately.

This is a clearly presented, very basic course about the Covid-19 virus, its natural history (insofar as we know it) and about contact tracing. I found myself getting bored and started reading the slides and skipping some of the audio. I was hoping for something a bit more sophisticated from Hopkins faculty.I found it difficult to navigate through the lectures without having to go back to  the "week 1" heading after each lecture or quiz. There should be a way to progress more smoothly through the coursework. I suspect this is a Coursera issue and not related to the lectures themselves, though. I also found it odd that I had to probe fairly hard to find the link to rate the course, though it took only seconds before I was "offered" the chance to purchase a certificate of completion.This is my second Coursera course. Compared to the first one, this one was a gem. However, compared to many of the "Great Courses" offerings, it fell flat.

This was a fine course covering the details very clearly. There are two suggestions I would like to make. First is to include a collection of Student Questions and Answers for each section. This would require a page where users could check past questions and upload questions they had after completing a section. It would also require someone to read questions submitted periodically and upload answers to those that they deem relevant. I know that the later is time intensive, but I think it could really improve learning.  I would also have liked more technical references or the material covered to be included in the Additional Resources, rather than just referring us to similar training materials from CDC and WHO. For example: What studies determined the Incubation Period? What studies determined that the Infectious Period should include (only) two days before signs or symptoms appear and not say five days?  (This clearly effects the number of contacts we trace...) Similarly there could be citations for general works on the ethics of contact tracing and for the communication framework you have chosen to adopt. Thanks

Thank you for the opportunity to take this course for free. I am a retired Director of Technology at a K-8 school. I was curious to learn more about the process of contact tracing and definitely felt that this course gave me a basic understanding of how the process works. I had thought about offering to volunteer to do contact tracing. However, after taking this course, I have the feeling I don't have the patience for it at this point in my life. If there were another way I could assist from home in fighting this virus, I would be willing to consider it.I appreciate having had this window into this very important process, which is essential to bringing down the number of deaths from this disease. The reason for 4 rather than 5 stars is for technical reasons. Though you said Coursera would work in Safari and Chrome (I tried both), there were a couple things that didn't work that annoyed me. One is that the transcript below the video showed maybe a paragraph. There was no ability to scroll through the text to see more. While you can download the script, it was hard to read. Fortunately, my hearing and sight are fine and this really didn't affect me, but... Also in the box where you take notes and somewhere around there I believe it said you could highlight text, I couldn't figure out how to make that work. Once again, while I don't want to pursue working as a COVID-19 contact tracer, I am grateful to have had the opportunity to understand how the process of contact tracing works. I will be here cheering the contact workers on!

Learning about technologies in China and South Korea that are unavailable to use here seemed fairly irrelevant. I can how this might be important in some situations (and perhaps later applications), but for the introductory course it seemed superfluous. The technology section in general was the weakest part of the course . . . it seems this is more sensibly delegated to training via the organization that hires the contact tracer since the protocols and available technologies will differ from region and each organization. I'd rather see more details about the virus itself and maybe even more communication strategies (esp. for example, dealing with people who refuse to isolate and believe the whole coronavirus crisis is 'fake'! Perhaps also, more of the 'unknowns,' disputed claims, or myths about the virus and its treatment and how to deal with those. But, otherwise, a very informative, clear and useful course. Thank you.

Overall, very good. The hard part was defining paraphrasing and reflecting properly. Some of your examples were not isolated enough. Like open ended questions and probing, paraphrasing and reflecting can happen in the same reply. As a point of information, latest news on surfaces contaminated by droplets is that FLOORS are carrying the virus home especially on tennis shoes (https://www.safetyandhealthmagazine.com/articles/19770-aerosol-transmission-of-covid-19-can-exceed-6-feet-shoes-can-spread-coronavirus-on-floors-study).  Your notes: 'Surfaces may have viruses from someoneâ€™s respiratory droplets', floors are surfaces. May need to clarify primary vs secondary. Reproductive number--I had a question--from https://www.news-medical.net/news/20200510/Reproduction-number-of-COVID-19-and-how-it-relates-to-public-health-measures.aspx: 'he first reported R0 was from Wuhan, at 2.2, as a result of direct contact tracing. This became suspect due to the volume of cases, leading to the breakdown of healthcare systems and inadequate testing facilities at that stage, as well as evolving case definitions. Even today, model choice, starting conditions, and other assumptions shape the final calculation, which has led to a wide range of R0 values from 2.2â€“3.6 to 4.1â€“6.5.' Aren't we seeing higher numbers than 2.2 on average? THANKS -- I am a retired PA and Professor, I thought being a tracer could be another interesting and helpful step in my life. Be well.

There are some things I disagree with; while I know it has unfortunately become the standard, accepted way of doing things in government and industry, paraphrasing and reflecting in the ways taught in this course have always irritated the hell out of me when I've been on the receiving end - they sound insincere, formulaic and contrived. Friends and family *never* say, "I understand that you're feeling blah blah blah right now..." - it's fake and it sounds it. Such things are uttered only by representatives of institutions, and for that reason they undermine rapport rather than building it. Or at least they do when *I'm* on the other end of the phone. Saying the case's or contact's name can be good, but not more than two or three times in one conversation. If you do it too often it comes to sound the same way as that fake paraphrasing/reflecting: like a transparent ploy to make you think that this person who doesn't know the first thing about you is in fact a familiar friend.I may have had some other complaints, but they were minor, and any complaints I did have were more than overshadowed by the pleasure of listening to Dr. Gurley's delightful voice and vocal mannerisms - she sounds whip-smart and adorable, a wildly appealing combination of traits. Be still my heart.  =)Coursera's navigation system does take some getting used to, and I kept thinking of one reviewer who complained that there was no certificate; I suspect he never figured out how the navigation works and thought he'd completed the course when in fact he'd only completed the first section. Be aware that the course takes around five hours to complete and comprises many modules and quizzes along the way, so if you think you've finished it in an hour or so...you haven't.Overall, a very satisfactory course (and it is kinda cool to have a certificate from Johns Hopkins). Thank you, Dr. Gurley!

Which of the following statements might build rapport with a case or contact? 
Select all that applySince only one statement was in fact correct the question could have been phrased : Which of the following statement(s) that are listed might build rapport with a case or contact?  The use of the plural form of statement without the (s) indicated there was in fact more than one answer and that choosing only one was certainly incorrect. The COVID-19 crisis has created an unprecedented need for contact tracing across the country, requiring thousands of people to learn key skills quickly. The job qualifications for contact tracing positions differ throughout the country and the world, with some new positions open to individuals with a high school diploma or equivalent. In this introductory course, students will learn about the science of SARS-CoV-2 , including the infectious period, the clinical presentation of COVID-19, and the evidence for how SARS-CoV-2 is transmitted from person-to-person and why contact tracing can be such an effective public health intervention. Students will learn about how contact tracing is done, including how to build rapport with cases, identify their contacts, and support both cases and their contacts to stop transmission in their communities. The course will also cover several important ethical considerations around contact tracing, isolation, and quarantine. Finally, the course will identify some of the most common barriers to contact tracing efforts -- along with strategies to overcome them

Overall my experience with this course was excellent.  I enjoyed the voice of the speaker and the speed of the speaking on topics that often were complex, as well as the relative thoroughness of coverage of a very broad topic.  One thing that I missed, and am wondering (did I experience study fatigue at this time???) was a discussion of the specific list of items/content that must be retrieved from a case or contact when calling them.  I also felt that the rationale was sometimes missing for why we need each item (eg. in "Addressing Process Complexities" it was not clear why I would ask how many days is someone having a cough or fever, why it is necessary to go through the entire list of symptoms (except to have a baseline perhaps on a first call?), and why the loss of taste and smell (a hallmark symptom of COVID-19) was not even mentioned?  Should telling the case/contact to call the PCP be a requirement?  suggestion?  That wasn't clear, but again, maybe I nodded off. ;)  I have other questions related to care of pets in a home, and whether or not a health care professional (eg. RN, MD) is allowed to give/suggest home care measures within the scope of their respective practices.  I don't remember this being mentioned.  Are contacts/cases supposed to keep a daily log of temperatures and symptoms?  Required?  Suggested?  Sorry for the lengthy review.  Again, overall, I loved this course and would recommend it to all of my colleagues in Nursing and College Health.  Thank you for this excellent presentation!

Very  informative, clearly stated, well organized and interesting.  I have only one "comment" - we were often asked "how much time did you spend on this module?"  I never really understood what constituted a full module - was it after every single quiz?  after a group of quizzes?  It didn't seem to happen after every quiz, but I was never sure how many videos I had watched and/or quizzes I had taken between "time checks."  But I think I can say that the entire course took me maybe 5-6 hours total time.  Also, when I was just about to take the final exam, there was a reference to "different standards" for NY State and NY City, but there was no link to find out the necessary information. This class not only subtly showcases the medical expertise of the instructors, it is designed extremely well allowing for easy absorption of the facts. It is readily apparent that the expertise of contact tracers was also incorporated into class, giving us very valuable tips on how to actually do the job of a contact tracer including what NOT to do. The updates included for CDC guidelines were extremely appreciated as these seem to change daily these days. Loved the videos of contact tracer conversations! Extremely helpful!I originally started a contact tracer course at my local junior college. It was immediately apparent to me that while the instructors were very knowledgeable, they were also practitioners and did not have the instructional expertise to develop a course that easily understandable for students. Having been a teacher for over 12 years, perhaps I was more biased, but in talking to my classmates online, everyone seemed to be struggling with the same issue. I have compared the class materials of each and realized that the John Hopkins coursera class actually gave me much more information regarding the actual experience of contact tracing, which is essentially why I took this course in the first place.Thank you for creating such an informative and easily understandable course!

I think that the contact tracers need to know the current limitations of testing for SARS-CoV antibodies, which may lack specificity and not reflect lasting immunity. This is evolving information. Please also differentiate and explain more clearly: exposure, infection, incubation period.The R0 is of course a useful parameter but begs the question of how it could range, depending on the number of contacts actually exposed to the index case. Should it be thought of as a ratio? This was confusing in the course. I think that showing graphs with geometric and exponential increases could be a helpful graphic. It would be a nice review of high-school math."Medical Grade mask" is a colloquial term. Better to describe different face coverings as artisanal/homemade, procedure or surgical, N95 respirator (looks like and could be used as a dust mask but is more than that). Also the N95 is designed to protect the wearer, so we often wear a surgical mask on top of it to protect our patients. Our other PPE elements such as gowns, face shields,  and gloves are part of the protection package for health care professionals.  I would like people to understand that any face covering used properly and  consistently can benefit the wearer and the people nearby

I would like an explanation here for all Contact Tracers, Contact Investigators, and their supervisors based on the Dept. of Health and Human Services as it related to PII, and what forms of information can be used to verify a Contact's identity. There's a big problem with that here. I see a lot of people don't understand it, including myself. In these examples, also, I see sometimes only the DOB is used and other times a DOB and Address were requested/confirmed. We do need solid examples and scenarios in order to properly maintain HIPAA rules and not get into trouble ourselves. We are currently using DOB and Address. If these are not available, we cannot make the call, even though we may also have linkable information along with linked information. It's better to be safe than sorry, but at what cost, if we can also verify by other PII means if some forms of PII are not available? Thank you

I am an elementary school nurse who @ the last minute has started off their school year in a virtual learning model.  We hope to go to hybrid p 1st quarter.  My nursing supervisor asked all of the district nurses to complete this course in the probable event we will be contract tracers for each of our buildings and to help our Human Resources dep't and the local health dep't to monitor COVID -19  concerns in the district.I found this course to be challenging as well as insightful into the world of public health.  It was extremely helpful to have non judgmental quizzes along the way to reinforce the learning.  The role playing videos were great learning tools.  Communication doesn't come easy for me, so being given examples of the appropriate words to say was paramount for me.  I know I will be able to try and build great rapport w/ any staff that I need to help.  Thank you!  I am a perfectionist by nature, so I know I sometimes get too caught up in what I am doing.  That being said, the hours I put into this course were far more than what the course elicited/ stated would need to be committed to.  I am a health professional so the anatomy/pathophysiology, nuts & bolts of SARS-CoV-2 came relatively easy.  This course did however take just about double the 6 -7 hours of commitment that was advertised.  That fact left me scrambling to add more study/ viewing time than I originally thought was needed.  Total time to complete, I feel, needs to be adjusted for future participants.  I know I will keep this in mind before signing up for another class.  Thank you for this format.Cheri

Moreover none of the political controversy is addressed. This is something contact tracers will doubtless have to encounter. There are no hints or suggestions on countering, dealing or dispensing with the anti-COVID propaganda aspect of contact tracing. On a more personal note, the presenter, though clearly competent and well-meaning, seems to have adopted a trendy frying voice, so that at times she sounds as if she were croaking out the information. This got old for me. My partner also commented on the voice in passing. Overall though, I was pleased with the course and grateful for the opportunity to learn about contact tracing.
